twitter-roberta-base-sentiment¶

In [129]:
from transformers import AutoModelForSequenceClassification
from transformers import TFAutoModelForSequenceClassification
from transformers import AutoTokenizer
import numpy as np
from scipy.special import softmax

def preprocess(text):
    new_text = []
 
 
    for t in text.split(" "):
        t = '@user' if t.startswith('@') and len(t) > 1 else t
        t = 'http' if t.startswith('http') else t
        new_text.append(t)
    return " ".join(new_text)
# Tasks:
# emoji, emotion, hate, irony, offensive, sentiment
# stance/abortion, stance/atheism, stance/climate, stance/feminist, stance/hillary
task= "sentiment"
MODEL = f"cardiffnlp/twitter-roberta-base-{task}"

tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(MODEL)

labels = [-1, 0, 1] # ['negative', 'neutral', 'positive']

# PT
model = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(MODEL)
model.save_pretrained(MODEL)

In [120]:
for sentence in sentences:
    text = preprocess(sentence)
    encoded_input = tokenizer(text, return_tensors='pt')
    output = model(**encoded_input)
    scores = output[0][0].detach().numpy()
    scores = softmax(scores)
    print(f"{sentence}\n  sentiment = {scores @ labels:.4f}\n")

def cosine_similarity(a, b):
    # Compute cosine similarity between two numpy vectors a and b
    return (a @ b)/(a@a * b@b)**0.5

similarity_matrix = pairwise_distances(cls_embeddings, metric=cosine_similarity) 

##### Plot the similarity matrix #####
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [12, 10] # Change figure size of the plot
plt.imshow(similarity_matrix) # Display an image in the plot
plt.colorbar() # Add colorbar to the plot
plt.yticks(ticks=range(len(sentences)), labels=sentences) # Set tick locations and labels (sentences) of y-axis
plt.title('Comparison of BERT Word Embeddings (cosine_similarity)') # Add title to the plot
for (i,j), label in np.ndenumerate(similarity_matrix): # np.ndenumerate is 2D version of enumerate
    plt.text(i, j, '{:.2f}'.format(label), ha='center', va='center') # Add values in similarity_matrix to the corresponding position in the plot
plt.show() # Show the plot

import random
from transformers import BertModel, BertTokenizerFast

# Fix random seed for reproducibility
def same_seeds(seed):
    torch.manual_seed(seed)
    if torch.cuda.is_available():
        torch.cuda.manual_seed(seed)
        torch.cuda.manual_seed_all(seed)
    np.random.seed(seed)
    random.seed(seed)
    torch.backends.cudnn.benchmark = False
    torch.backends.cudnn.deterministic = True

same_seeds(0)

import datetime as dt
from sklearn import linear_model
from sklearn.feature_selection import f_regression

def shiftdate(startDate, days):
    return startDate + dt.timedelta(days=days)
def getRegressionCoef(startDate, endDate, Series_keyDate):
    Y = Series_keyDate.iloc[(Series_keyDate.index >= startDate) & (Series_keyDate.index <= endDate)]
    X = [(d - startDate).days for d in Series_keyDate.index  if (d >= startDate and d <= endDate)]
    regr = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    regr.fit(np.array(X).reshape(-1, 1),Y)
    
    return {"X":[shiftdate(startDate,X[0]),shiftdate(startDate,X[-1])],
            "Y":np.array([X[0], X[-1]]) *regr.coef_[0] + regr.intercept_,
            "coef":regr.coef_[0], 
            "bias":regr.intercept_,
            "t":f_regression(np.array(X).reshape(-1, 1),Y)[1][0]}

DNN model¶

Since the similarity(pre,post) $\approx$ similarity(pre,pre) $\approx$ similarity(post,post), we can conclude that the writing-style of every news is invariant over time.

Training a deep-model with 80% preElection data, we expect the model can predict postElection behavior as well as another 20% preElection behavior.

Data Distribution¶

Maybe... there exits semantic/topic differences between datasets

In [1020]:
def findTopN_more_freq(featureName, TFIDF_Matrix, N):
    """
    return top N important words of a dataset
    """
    ind = np.argsort(TFIDF_Matrix.toarray().sum(axis = 0))[::-1][0:N]
    return (np.array(featureName)[ind])
